TY  - JOUR
AU  - Karantounias, Anastasios G
T1  - Optimal Fiscal Policy with Recursive Preferences
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdy005
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 85
IS  - 4
SP  - 2283
EP  - 2317
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - I study the implications of recursive utility, a popular preference specification in macro-finance, for the design of optimal fiscal policy. Standard Ramsey tax-smoothing prescriptions are substantially altered. The planner over-insures by taxing less in bad times and more in good times, mitigating the effects of shocks. At the intertemporal margin, there is a novel incentive for introducing distortions that can lead to an ex-ante capital subsidy. Overall, optimal policy calls for a much stronger use of debt returns as a fiscal absorber, leading to the conclusion that actual fiscal policy is even worse than we thought.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdy005
ER  - 



