TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hébert, Benjamin
T1  - Moral Hazard and the Optimality of Debt
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdx080
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 85
IS  - 4
SP  - 2214
EP  - 2252
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - I show that, in a benchmark model, debt securities minimize the welfare losses associated with the moral hazards of excessive risk-taking and lax effort. For any security design, the variance of the security payoff is a statistic that summarizes these welfare losses. Debt securities have the least variance, among all limited liability securities with the same expected value. In other models, mixtures of debt and equity are exactly optimal, and pure debt securities are approximately optimal. I study both static and dynamic security design problems, and show that these two types of problems are equivalent. I use moral hazard in mortgage lending as a recurring example, but my results apply to other corporate finance and principal-agent problems.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdx080
ER  - 



